recon.backingstore_trait:
The seam that lets durable virtio-blk slot in later WITHOUT touching tier logic (M13 is RAM-backed; the docs/ROADMAP risk note explicitly defers durable backing). In crates/tb-hal/src/mem.rs, object-safe, alloc-only, zero unsafe:

```
pub enum Region { Episodic, Semantic, Working }   // tier-tagged streams
pub enum MemErr { Full, NotFound, Io }
pub trait BackingStore {
    fn append(&mut self, region: Region, bytes: &[u8]) -> Result<u64 /*offset*/, MemErr>;
    fn read_at(&self, region: Region, off: u64, buf: &mut [u8]) -> Result<usize, MemErr>;
    fn flush(&mut self) -> Result<(), MemErr>;
    fn epoch(&self) -> u64;   // freshness marker: T2 raw = instant RYW; derived T3 carries a visible epoch (Zep counter-example)
}
```

DEFAULT M13 IMPL — `pub struct RamStore { ep: Vec<u8>, sem: Vec<u8>, wm: Vec<u8>, epoch: u64 }` over the M5/M7 kernel heap: `append` extends the per-region Vec and bumps `epoch`; `flush` is a no-op; fully in-RAM. MemSubstrate is generic/boxed over the store (`backing: alloc::boxed::Box<dyn BackingStore>` or a type param) so a future `VirtioBlkStore` (durable, behind the M16-era virtio ring — the ONLY unsafe, isolated in arch) drops in unchanged. Token write-amplification is metered through a `Quota` (KeyKOS space-bank analogy) so unbounded userspace derivation cannot blow the journal.
